<h3>Activity description</h3>

<p style="margin-left: 1cm">The main goal of BerliOS is to support the different interest groups in the area of Open Source Software (OSS) and thereby to offer a neutral mediator function. The target groups of BerliOS are on one hand the developers and users of Open Source software and on the other hand commercial manufacturers of OSS operating systems and applications as well as support companies.

<p style="margin-left: 1cm"><b>Users</b>

<p style="margin-left: 1cm">Besides private users of Open Source software small to mid-size enterprises (SMEs) as well as the public administration are important target groups BerliOS will address. It will be pointed out in which application areas entire OSS solutions are already available today and are applicable in production fields.

<p style="margin-left: 1cm">In dialogue with the users of particular trades missing components will be identified, which still averts OSS solutions to come into operation today. The development of these missing components shall then be initiated by contacting software manufacturers or free developer groups to realize corresponding components.

<p style="margin-left: 1cm">Another main focus will be the provision of general information about the OSS community. Among other thinks this includes web-based documentation, databases for software, hardware and products, news, event notes as well as search engines.
Furthermore existing solutions into operation in particular trades are presented and documented. Discussion forums supports the exchange of experience between the users of OSS solutions. Finally the most important Web and FTP servers are mirrored to offer the world-wide developed Open Source software and documentation in the national (Germany) domain extensive and fast.

<p style="margin-left: 1cm">The following information and services are offered to users:

<ul style="margin-left: 1cm">
<li><b>Documentation</b>
<br>The world-wide emerging documentation about Open Source software is classified by BerliOS and is provided to the public via the world-wide web. The documentation contains HOWTO and FAQ documents, free books and books directories, as well as standards and other documents. Beside the offering of English documents a main goal of BerliOS is the provision of information in German language.
</li>
<p style="margin-left: 1cm">
<li><b>Databases</b>
<br>Through databases extensive information is offered to users about Open Source distributions and application software, hardware and software products as well as support services and companies. With an easy to use interface recherche functions can be initiated by users.
</li>
<p style="margin-left: 1cm">
<li><b>News &amp; Events</b>
<br>Recent news and event notes about Open Source topics are offered in a compact form.
</li>
<p style="margin-left: 1cm">
<li><b>Software Archives</b>
<br>The main archives of world-wide developed Open Source software are mirrored to support an extensive software offering with fast access in the national domain (Germany).
Downloads are provided by World-wide Web and FTP.
</li>
<p style="margin-left: 1cm">
<li><b>Solutions for particular trades</b>
<br>Existing solutions in particular companies are introduced and documented. The experience gained during realization and deployment then can be used as an example for implementation in other companies to show chances and risks. BerliOS offers a technical infrastructure for the exchange of experience between users and provide a mediator function between users and developers as well as support companies.
</li>
<p style="margin-left: 1cm">
<li>
<b>Software Exchange</b>
<br>For free developer groups incentives are provided by an Open Source Software Exchange. In the market particular enterprises, interest groups or the government will offer an amount of money for a needed solution. The developers which supplies the components first will gain the money.
</li>
<p style="margin-left: 1cm">
<li><b>Search Engine</b>
<br>Besides our own search engine enabling users to find information on the BerliOS Web server an additional directory of other world-wide existing search engines is offered.
</li>
</ul>

<p style="margin-left: 1cm" ><b>Developers</b>

<p style="margin-left: 1cm">A server-based infrastructure will be provided for the developers of Open Source software. The administrative tools supports the joint coordinated software development between people who live and work at different geographical places.

<p style="margin-left: 1cm">For free developer groups incentives shall be provided by an Open Source Software Exchange. In the market particular enterprises, interest groups or the government will offer an amount of money for a needed solution. The developers which supplies the components first will gain the money.

<p style="margin-left: 1cm">The motivation for software manufacturers to develop commercial products results from demand analyses in particular trades which shows a market gap. 

<p style="margin-left: 1cm">For the realization of Open Source projects the following services are provided free of charge:

<ul style="margin-left: 1cm">
<li>
<b>Software Repositories with Version Control</b>
<br>Each project gets its own CVS repository with separate CVSROOT. Developers are granted secure read/write access to the tree through SSH. Anonymous CVS/pserver read access is granted to the general public.
</li>
<p style="margin-left: 1cm">
<li>
<b>Web Server</b>
<br>Each project gets its own web directory for presentation purposes. An own CGI directory allows the execution of scripts. The domain is hosted on a name-based VirtualHost on the main project web server.
</li>
<p style="margin-left: 1cm">
<li>
<b>FTP Server</b>
<br>Each project gets its own FTP directory. Developers are granted to upload files. Anonymous users are granted to download files only.
</li>
<p style="margin-left: 1cm">
<li>
<b>Database</b>
<br>Each project gets its own MySQL database the web server has access to. An web-based interface allows the administration of the database for developers.
</li>
<p style="margin-left: 1cm">
<li>
<b>Mailing Lists</b>
<br>Each project can create and manage its own mailing lists. There exist two different types. Every user is able to become a member of an open mailing list. But only an administrator is able to add a new member to a closed one.
</li>
<p style="margin-left: 1cm">
<li>
<b>Discussion Forums</b>
<br>Discussion forums provide the exchange of experience, requests for help and development, etc.
</li>
<p style="margin-left: 1cm">
<li>
<b>Bug Tracking</b>
<br>Reporting bugs and its management is supported by a bug tracking system.
</li>
<p style="margin-left: 1cm">
<li>
<b>Surveys and Rating</b>
<br>Surveys can be performed by each project to get a valuation or to recognize trends and user wishes in the preliminary stages of development.
</li>
<p style="margin-left: 1cm">
<li>
<b>News</b>
<br>Each project can provide and manage its own news.
</li>
<p style="margin-left: 1cm">
<li>
<b>Project Management</b>
<br>By the use of a web browser as well as the server-based administration tools an easy maintenance is provided for all facets of a project.
</li>
<p style="margin-left: 1cm">
<li>
<b>Project Map</b>
<br>All projects hosted from BerliOS will be organized thematically and listed in a project map.
</li>
<p style="margin-left: 1cm">
<li>
<b>Software Exchange</b>
<br>In the market particular enterprises, interest groups or the government will offer an amount of money for a needed solution. The developers which supplies the components first will gain the money.
</li>
</ul>

<p style="margin-left: 1cm"><b>Manufacturers, Distributors &amp; Support Companies</b>

<p style="margin-left: 1cm">The application of Open Source software in business environment creates a need for high quality consultancy, technical support and training leading to job creation in a new dynamic industry sector. BerliOS will support this process by acting as information switchboard and clearing house between demand and supply side of Open Source support services.

<p style="margin-left: 1cm">A neutral platform will be provided to present products from manufacturers of operating system distributions and applications as well as support companies:

<ul style="margin-left: 1cm">
<li><b>Databases</b>
<br>Through the provision of databases for companies, products and services and its thematically structuring the users gets the possibility to find information they really need. Within the scope of the allowed structure companies are able to define its contents by itself and to update it whenever needed reflecting the actual status.
</li>
</ul>

<h3>Public Domain Software and Labs</h3>

<p style="margin-left: 1cm">The preponderant part of the server-based application software to manage OSS development projects and to generate dynamic Web content using databases as well as the complete documentation is based on Open Source components and will be freely available over the Internet.

